Estonia has become richer by one new fish species. The fish, named Lääne-Lont or Mudila, is the eighty-ninth fish species found in Estonian waters.
Yesterday morning, while conducting fish monitoring near the port of Sillamäe, Estonian fish researchers caught two specimens of the new species. The new alien species, Lääne-Lont or Mudila, is about ten centimeters long and can easily be mistaken for local mudila species.
However, the new alien species can be identified by its elongated nostrils. Previously, Lääne-Lont or Mudila has only been caught once in the Baltic Sea, in the year 2007, in Russian waters.
Like most alien species, this fish also arrived in our waters through ballast water from ships. Lääne-Lont or Mudila's native habitat is in the Caspian and Black Seas, which is why it has not been able to reproduce abundantly in our cold waters.
I could assume that it won't cause any major disruptions in our aquatic ecosystems, but, but, but like all living organisms, they still compete with our native species for food and habitat. However, I believe that the impact won't be as drastic as with the round goby.
